# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uracil
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu was discovered on 10 May 1999 by astronomers with the Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research at the Lincoln Lab's ETS near Socorro, New Mexico, in the United States.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It was given the provisional designation 1999 JU3.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The asteroid was officially named "Ryugu" by the Minor Planet Center on 28 September 2015 (M.P.C.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The name refers to Ryūgū-jō (Dragon Palace), a magical underwater palace in a Japanese folktale.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] In the story, the fisherman Urashima Tarō travels to the palace on the back of a turtle, and when he returns, he carries with him a mysterious box, much like *Hayabusa2* returning with samples.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu formed as part of an asteroid family, belonging either to Eulalia or Polana.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Those asteroid families are most likely fragments of past asteroid collisions.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The large number of boulders on the surface supports a catastrophic disruption of the parent body.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The parent body of Ryugu probably experienced dehydration due to internal heating and must have formed in an environment without a strong magnetic field.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] After this catastrophic disruption, part of the surface was reshaped again by the high speed rotation of the asteroid forming the equatorial ridge (Ryujin Dorsum), through internal failure and/or mass wasting.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The geologically distinct western area ('Western bulge') is probably the result of asymmetrical internal failure.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It is hoped that surface samples will help to reveal more of the geological history of the asteroid.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu is hypothesized to be an extinct comet.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu orbits the Sun at a distance of 0.96–1.41 AU once every 16 months (474 days; semi-major axis of 1.19 AU).
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.19 and an inclination of 6° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It has a minimum orbital intersection distance with Earth of 95,443.442 km (0.000638 AU), equivalent to 0.23 lunar distances.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Müller *et al.* used data from a number of observatories, and suggested that the asteroid was "almost spherical", a fact that hinders precise conclusions, with retrograde rotation, an effective diameter of 0.85–0.88 km (0.528 miles) and a geometric albedo of 0.044 to 0.050.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] They estimated that the grain sizes of its surface materials are between 1 and 10 mm.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Initial images taken by the *Hayabusa2* spacecraft on approach at a distance of 700 km (430 mi) were released on 14 June 2018.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] They revealed a diamond-shaped body 1 km in diameter and confirmed its retrograde motion.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Between 17 and 18 June 2018, *Hayabusa2* went from 330 to 240 km (210 to 150 mi) from Ryugu and captured a series of additional images from the closer approach.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Astronomer Brian May created stereoscopic images from data collected a few days later.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] After a few months of exploration, JAXA scientists concluded that Ryugu is actually a rubble pile with about 50% of its volume being empty space.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The acceleration due to gravity at the equator has been evaluated at about 0.11 mm/s2, rising to 0.15 mm/s2 at the poles.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The mass of Ryugu is estimated at 450 million tonnes.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The asteroid has a volume of 0.377 ± 0.005 km3 and a bulk density of 1.19 ± 0.03 g/cm3 based on the shape model.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu has a round shape with an equatorial ridge, called Ryujin Dorsum.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu is a spinning top-shape asteroid similar to Bennu.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The ridge was shaped by strong centrifugal forces during a phase of high-speed rotation, through landslides and/or internal failure.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The western side, also called the western bulge, has a distinct shape.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It has a smooth surface with a sharp equatorial ridge.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] When modeling a high-speed rotation of present-day Ryugu, subsurface material appears structurally intact and relaxed in the western bulge, while other regions are more sensitive to structural failure.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This indicates past structural failure in the western bulge (only the elements that did not experience structural failure previously are now sensitive to failure).
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The western bulge is bordered by the Tokoyo and Horai Fossae.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Observations from *Hayabusa2* showed that the surface of Ryugu is very young and has an age of 8.9 ± 2.5 million years based on the data collected from the artificial crater that was created with an explosive by *Hayabusa2*.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The surface of Ryugu is porous and contains no or very little dust.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The measurements with the radiometer on board of MASCOT, which is called MARA, showed a low thermal conductivity of the boulders.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This was an in situ measurement of the high porosity of the boulder material.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This result showed that most meteorites originating from C-type asteroids are too fragile to survive the entry into Earth's atmosphere.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The images from the camera of MASCOT, which is called MASCam, showed that surface of Ryugu contains two different almost black types of rock with little internal cohesion, but no dust was detected.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] One type of rocky material on the surface is brighter with a smooth surface and sharp edges.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The other type of rock is dark with a cauliflower-like, crumbly surface.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The dark type of rock has a dark matrix with small, bright, spectrally different inclusions.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The inclusions appear similar to CI chondrites.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] An unanticipated side effect from the *Hayabusa2* thrusters revealed a coating of dark, fine-grained red material.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu shows variations of crater density that cannot be explained by randomness of cratering.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] There are more craters at lower latitudes and fewer at higher latitudes, and fewer craters in the western bulge (160°E – 290°E) than in the region around the meridian (300°E – 30°E).
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This variation is seen as evidence of a complicated geologic history of Ryugu.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The surface has one artificial crater, which was intentionally formed by the Small Carry-on Impactor (SCI), which was deployed by *Hayabusa2*.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] SCI fired a 2 kg copper mass onto the surface of Ryugu on 5 April 2019.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The artificial crater showed a darker subsurface material.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It created an Ejecta of 1 cm thickness and excavated material from up to 1 metre in depth.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu contains 4,400 boulders with a size larger than 5 metres.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu has more large boulders per surface area than Itokawa or Bennu, about one boulder larger than 20 metres per 50 km2.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The boulders resemble laboratory impact fragments.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The high number of boulders is explained with a catastrophic disruption of Ryugu's larger parent body.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The largest boulder, called Otohime, has a size of ~160 × 120 × 70 m and is too large to be explained as an ejected boulder from a crater.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] After the initial description (phase-1), part of the sample was distributed to the Hayabusa2 Initial Analysis Team, consisting of six sub-teams, and two Phase-2 curation institutes at Okayama University and JAMSTEC Kochi Institute for Core Sample Research.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] In March 2026, all five canonical nucleobases were found from these samples.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The deuterium-rich and nitrogen-15-rich isotopic compositions of fine-grained minerals and organics suggests that the parent body of Ryugu formed in the outer Solar System.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Titanium, chromium and molybdenum isotopic anomalies provide more evidence that ties Ryugu's origin to the outer Solar System.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Based on preserved magnetism in the samples researchers concluded that the parent body of Ryugu was probably formed in the darkness of nebular gas.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The Hayabusa2 sample capsule was significantly upgraded from Hayabusa, to preserve water, light organics, gases, and other volatiles.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This water was successfully sampled and preserved.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Via a bulk sample (~95 milligrams), its water content was reported as 6.84 ±0.34 wt%.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Independently, a research group with a far smaller allocation (particles) reported 4–7 percent water.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The lower-than-expected water signature seen by Hayabusa2 instruments was the result of space weathering, producing a dehydrated rind.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Carbonated liquid water was discovered in one crystal.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The water contained salts and organic matter.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The liquid water was found inside a hexagonal iron sulfide crystal.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The carbon dioxide was most likely CO2-ice (dry ice) inside the parent body.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The water ice melted soon after the parent body formed and the CO2 dissolved into the water.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Crystals "shaped like coral reefs" were found.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] These crystals probably formed in liquid water, which was once present in the interior of the parent body.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The parent body had a dryer surface and a wetter interior.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] After the collision of the parent body with a smaller asteroid, the interior and surface material were mixed.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Today Ryugu has both interior and parent body surface material on its surface.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] An international team found particles in the samples that contained small amounts of material unaltered by water.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The team found about 0.5 vol% of anhydrous silicates.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The isotopic analysis of the magnesium-rich olivine and pyroxene in the sample suggests that two types of high-temperature objects accreted onto the surface of Ryugu: amoeboid olivine aggregates and magnesium-rich chondrules.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Hayabusa2 recovered helium and other noble gases.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Some terrestrial contamination entered the system, but the Ryugu components are still measurable.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Aliphatic carbon-rich organics associated with coarse-grained phyllosilicates were found.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Such an association has not been observed in any meteorite study and could be unique to the asteroid Ryugu.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] In samples retrieved on Ryugu from the Japanese *Hayabusa2* spacecraft, scientists discovered 20 different amino acids.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] In March 2023, scientists announced that uracil and vitamin B3 were detected in samples retrieved from Ryugu.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Unlike previous instances when nucleobases and vitamins were found in certain carbon-rich meteorites, the samples were collected directly from the asteroid and delivered to Earth in sealed capsules, which meant Earthside contamination was not possible.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] NanoSIMS-based analysis at the Carnegie Institution found that the Ryugu samples contained grains older than the solar system.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The abundance and composition of these presolar grains were similar when compared to presolar grains in CI chondrites.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Researchers using the particle accelerator in J-PARC, used Muon beams to analyse the chemical composition of the samples.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The researchers found a similar composition when compared to CI chondrites, but a 25% lower oxygen abundance relative to silicon for the Ryugu samples.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The oxygen excess in meteorites might come from contamination after they entered earth's atmosphere.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] No magnetic field was detected near Ryugu on a global or local scale.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This measurement is based on the magnetometer on board of MASCOT, which is called MasMag.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This shows that Ryugu does not generate a magnetic field, indicating that the larger body from which it was fragmented was not generated in an environment with a strong magnetic field.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This result cannot be generalized for C-type asteroids, however, because the surface of Ryugu seems to have been recreated in a catastrophic disruption.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] As of August 2019, there are 13 surface features that are named by the IAU.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The three landing sites are not officially confirmed but are referred to by specific names in media by JAXA.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The theme of features on Ryugu is "children's stories".
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu was the first object to introduce the feature type known as the *saxa*, referring to the large boulders found on Ryugu's surface.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Ryugu is the first astronomical object with them being named.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Two boulders have been named "Styx" and "Small Styx" unofficially by the JAXA team; it is unknown if these names will be submitted for IAU approval.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] JAXA has given informal names to the specific landing and collection sites.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) spacecraft *Hayabusa2* was launched in December 2014 and successfully arrived at the asteroid on 27 June 2018.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It returned material from the asteroid to Earth in December 2020.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The *Hayabusa2* mission includes four rovers with various scientific instruments.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The rovers are named HIBOU (aka Rover-1A), OWL (aka Rover-1B), MASCOT and Rover-2 (aka MINERVA-II-2).
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] On 21 September 2018, the first two of these rovers, HIBOU and OWL (together the MINERVA-II-1 rovers) which hop around the surface of the asteroid, were released from *Hayabusa2*.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] This marks the first time a mission has completed a successful landing on a fast-moving asteroid body.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] On 3 October 2018, the German-French Mobile Asteroid Surface Scout (MASCOT) lander successfully arrived on Ryugu, ten days after the MINERVA rovers landed.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Its mission was short-lived, as was planned; the lander had only 16 hours of battery power and no way to recharge.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The last rover, Rover-2 or MINERVA-II-2, failed before release from the *Hayabusa2* orbiter.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It was deployed anyway on 2 October 2019 in orbit around Ryugu to perform gravitational measurements.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] It impacted the asteroid a few days after release.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] On 13 November 2019, commands were sent to *Hayabusa2* to leave Ryugu and begin its journey back to Earth.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] On 6 December 2020 (Australian time), a capsule containing the samples landed in Australia and after a brief search was retrieved.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Prior to the sample capsule return, the amount of sample was expected to be at least 0.1 g.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] The description of overall bulk sample was planned to be done by JAXA in the first six months.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] 5 wt% of the sample will be allocated for the detailed analysis by JAXA.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] 15 wt% will be allocated for initial analysis, and 10 wt% for "phase 2" analysis among Japanese research groups.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] Within a year, NASA (10 wt%) and international "phase 2" research groups (5 wt%) will receive their allotment.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] 15 wt% will be allocated for research proposals by international Announcement of Opportunity.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] 40 wt% of the sample will be stored unused for future analysis.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] After the sample capsule returned, the amount of retrieved sample turned out to be about 5.4 g.
[src:uracil/162173-ryugu] 162173 Ryugu is the setting of Daniel Suarez's novel Delta-V, describing the adventures of eight space miners who explore near-Earth asteroid Ryugu.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] The substance is a historically relevant anti-thyroid preparation.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] Edwin Astwood used it in 1943 as therapy for Graves' disease for the first time.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] Thiouracil inhibits thyroid activity by blocking the enzyme thyroid peroxidase.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] Its use in recent times has been replaced by advent of more potent and safer antithyroid drugs.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] It occurs in seeds of Brassica and Crucifera species.
[src:uracil/2-thiouracil] Thiouracil has been used as antithyroid, coronary vasodilator, and in congestive heart failure although its use has been largely supplanted by other drugs.
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] It has 520-fold selectivity for the adenosine A2A receptor over the adenosine A1 receptor (Ki = 54 nM and 28,000 nM for the rat receptors, respectively).
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] Its affinities for the adenosine A2B and A3 receptors are similarly low (Ki = 8,200 nM and >10,000 nM, respectively).
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] CSC has been found to reverse the catalepsy induced by the dopamine D1 receptor antagonist SCH-23390 and the dopamine D2 receptor antagonists raclopride and sulpiride in animals.
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] The drug was one of the first selective adenosine A2A receptor antagonists to be developed.
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] However, in addition to its adenosine receptor antagonism, CSC was subsequently found to be a potent monoamine oxidase B (MAO-B) inhibitor (Ki = 80.6 nM for baboon MAO-B).
[src:uracil/3-chlorostyrylcaffeine] CSC was first described in the scientific literature by 1993.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Side effects of use by injection are common.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] They may include inflammation of the mouth, loss of appetite, low blood cell counts, hair loss, and inflammation of the skin.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] When used as a cream, irritation at the site of application usually occurs.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Use of either form in pregnancy may harm the fetus.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorouracil is in the antimetabolite and pyrimidine analog families of medications.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] How it works is not entirely clear, but it is believed to involve blocking the action of thymidylate synthase and thus stopping the production of DNA.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorouracil was patented in 1956 and came into medical use in 1962.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] In 2023, it was the 267th most commonly prescribed medication in the United States, with more than 900,000 prescriptions.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorouracil has been given systemically for anal, breast, colorectal, oesophageal, stomach, pancreatic and skin cancers (especially head and neck cancers).
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] It has also been given topically (on the skin) for actinic keratosis, skin cancers and Bowen's disease (a type of cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma), and as eye drops for treatment of ocular surface squamous neoplasia.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Other uses include ocular injections into a previously created trabeculectomy bleb to inhibit healing and cause scarring of tissue, thus allowing adequate aqueous humor flow to reduce intraocular pressure.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] 5-Fluorouracil has application in the synthesis of fostamatinib.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorouracil is contraindicated in patients who are severely debilitated and in patients with bone marrow suppression due to either radiotherapy or chemotherapy.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] It is likewise contraindicated in pregnant or breastfeeding women.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Non-topical use, i.e. administration by injection, should be avoided in patients who do not have malignant illnesses.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] In 2020, the EU and UK license was updated to state that fluorouracil was contra-indicated in patients that "have a known complete absence of dihydropyrimidine dehydrogenase (DPD) activity".
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Within the UK, DPYD testing to check for this contraindication is now routine practice; this is not the case in the US.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Diarrhea is severe and may be dose-limiting and is exacerbated by co-treatment with calcium folinate.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Neutropenia tends to peak about 9–14 days after beginning treatment.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Thrombocytopenia tends to peak about 7–17 days after the beginning of treatment and tends to recover about 10 days after its peak.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Cardiotoxicity is a fairly common side effect, usually manifesting as angina or symptoms associated with coronary artery spasm, but about 0.55% of those receiving the drug will develop life-threatening cardiotoxicity.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Life-threatening cardiotoxicity includes: arrhythmias, ventricular tachycardia and cardiac arrest, secondary to transmural ischaemia.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The United States package insert warns that acute cerebellar syndrome has been observed following injection of fluorouracil and may persist after cessation of treatment.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Symptoms include ataxia, nystagmus, and dysmetria.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] There is very little difference between the minimum effective dose and maximum tolerated dose of 5-FU, and the drug exhibits marked individual pharmacokinetic variability.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Therefore, an identical dose of 5-FU may result in a therapeutic response with acceptable toxicity in some patients and unacceptable and possibly life-threatening toxicity in others.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Both overdosing and underdosing are of concern with 5-FU, although several studies have shown that the majority of colorectal cancer patients treated with 5-FU are underdosed based on today's dosing standard, body surface area (BSA).
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The limitations of BSA-based dosing prevent oncologists from being able to accurately titer the dosage of 5-FU for the majority of individual patients, which results in sub-optimal treatment efficacy or excessive toxicity.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Numerous studies have found significant relationships between concentrations of 5-FU in blood plasma and both desirable or undesirable effects on patients.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Studies have also shown that dosing based on the concentration of 5-FU in plasma can greatly increase desirable outcomes while minimizing negative side effects of 5-FU therapy.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] One such test that has been shown to successfully monitor 5-FU plasma levels and which "may contribute to improved efficacy and safety of commonly used 5-FU-based chemotherapies" is the My5-FU test.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Uridine Triacetate is a potential antidote for cases of suspected overdose.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The US Food and Drug Administration has highlighted the dangers of inadvertent administration to pets.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] While fluorouracil is sometimes used off label to treat horses, its administration to dogs in particular can be fatal.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The FDA reports that it has received 20 reports of fatal outcomes in dogs following accidental ingestion of topical fluorouracil.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] It may increase the INR and prothrombin times in people on warfarin.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorouracil's efficacy is decreased when used alongside allopurinol, which can be used to decrease fluorouracil induced stomatitis through use of allopurinol mouthwash.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The dihydropyrimidine dehydrogenase (DPD) enzyme is responsible for the detoxifying metabolism of fluoropyrimidines, a class of drugs that includes 5-fluorouracil, capecitabine, and tegafur.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Genetic variations within the DPD gene (*DPYD*) can lead to reduced or absent DPD activity, and individuals who are heterozygous or homozygous for these variations may have partial or complete DPD deficiency; an estimated 0.2% of individuals have complete DPD deficiency.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Those with partial or complete DPD deficiency have a significantly increased risk of severe or even fatal drug toxicities when treated with fluoropyrimidines; examples of toxicities include myelosuppression, neurotoxicity and hand-foot syndrome.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] 5-FU acts in several ways and is classically described as a thymidylate synthase (TS) inhibitor.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Interrupting the action of this enzyme blocks synthesis of the pyrimidine thymidylate (dTMP), which is a nucleotide required for DNA replication.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Thymidylate synthase methylates deoxyuridine monophosphate (dUMP) to form thymidine monophosphate (dTMP).
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Administration of 5-FU causes a scarcity in dTMP, so rapidly dividing cancerous cells undergo cell death via thymineless death.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Calcium folinate provides an exogenous source of reduced folinates and hence stabilises the 5-FU-TS complex, hence enhancing 5-FU's cytotoxicity.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] 5-FU is also converted inside cells into 5-fluorouridine triphosphate (5FUTP), which can be incorporated into RNA (especially ribosomal RNA, tRNA, snRNA, and mRNA) in place of uridine.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] 5-FU incorporation into precursor rRNA impairs rRNA processing and maturation.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Incorporation into small nuclear RNA (snRNA), particularly U2 snRNA, inhibits pseudouridylation, and results in faulty pre-mRNA splicing.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] In 1954, Abraham Cantarow and Karl Paschkis found liver tumors absorbed radioactive uracil more readily than did normal liver cells.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Charles Heidelberger, who had earlier found that fluorine in fluoroacetic acid inhibited a vital enzyme, asked Robert Duschinsky and Robert Schnitzer at Hoffmann-La Roche to synthesize fluorouracil.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Some credit Heidelberger and Duschinsky with the discovery that 5-fluorouracil markedly inhibited tumors in mice.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The original 1957 report In 1958, Anthony R.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Waisman, and Charles Heidelberger reported the first clinical findings of 5-FU's activity in cancer in humans.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] In 2003, scientists isolated 5-fluorouracil and 4 closely related compounds from the marine sponge, *Phakellia fusca*, collected near Woody Island of the Paracel Islands in the South China Sea.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] Fluorine-containing natural products are extremely rare with few examples such as monofluoroacetate.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The name "fluorouracil" is the INN, USAN, USP name, and BAN.
[src:uracil/5-fluorouracil] The form "5-fluorouracil" is often used; it shows that there is a fluorine atom on the 5th carbon of a uracil ring.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] The chemical compound **5-methyluridine** (symbol **m5U**), also called **ribothymidine** (rT), is a pyrimidine nucleoside.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] It is the ribonucleoside counterpart to the deoxyribonucleoside thymidine, which lacks a hydroxyl group at the 2' position.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] 5-Methyluridine contains a thymine base joined to a ribose pentose sugar.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] m5U is one of the most common modifications made to cellular RNA.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] It almost universally occurs in position 54 (part of the T arm) of eukaryotic and bacterial tRNA, serving to stabilize the molecule.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] The same "T-loop" motif occurs in many other forms of noncoding RNA such as tmRNA and rRNA.
[src:uracil/5-methyluridine] Loss of the tRNA modification does not usually produce a different, less fit, phenotype.
[src:uracil/7-methylxanthine] It is shown that systemic treatment with 7-MX appears to be efficient in retarding axial elongation and myopia progression among myopic children.
[src:uracil/7-methylxanthine] The treatment is safe and without side effects, and may be continued until 18–20 years of age, when age-related cross-linking of collagen prevents further elongation of the eye.
[src:uracil/7-methylxanthine] Additionally, further studies show that oral intake of 7-MX was associated with reduced myopia progression and reduced axial elongation in this sample of myopic children from Denmark.
[src:uracil/7-methylxanthine] Randomized controlled trials are needed to determine whether the association is causal.
[src:uracil/8-chlorotheophylline] Despite being classified as a xanthine stimulant, 8-chlorotheophylline generally does not produce any hyperlocomotion above control in mice and does not appear to cross the blood–brain barrier well.
[src:uracil/8-chlorotheophylline] The 8-chloro modification is not selected for pharmacological properties; instead, it was to raise the acidity of the xanthine amine group enough to form a co-salt with diphenhydramine.
[src:uracil/8-chlorotheophylline] The drug is also sold in combination with promethazine as a salt.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil is a common and naturally occurring pyrimidine derivative.
[src:uracil/uracil] The name "uracil" was coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.
[src:uracil/uracil] Originally discovered in 1900 by Alberto Ascoli, it was isolated by hydrolysis of yeast nuclein; it was also found in bovine thymus and spleen, herring sperm, and wheat germ.
[src:uracil/uracil] It is a planar, unsaturated compound that has the ability to absorb light.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil that was formed extraterrestrially has been detected in the Murchison meteorite, in near-Earth asteroid Ryugu, and possibly on the surface of the moon Titan.
[src:uracil/uracil] It has been synthesized under cold laboratory conditions similar to outer space, from pyrimidine embedded in water ice and exposed to ultraviolet light.
[src:uracil/uracil] In RNA, uracil base-pairs with adenine and replaces thymine during DNA transcription.
[src:uracil/uracil] In DNA, the evolutionary substitution of thymine for uracil may have increased DNA stability and improved the efficiency of DNA replication (discussed below).
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil pairs with adenine through hydrogen bonding.
[src:uracil/uracil] When base pairing with adenine, uracil acts as both a hydrogen bond acceptor and a hydrogen bond donor.
[src:uracil/uracil] In RNA, uracil binds with a ribose sugar to form the ribonucleoside uridine.
[src:uracil/uracil] When a phosphate attaches to uridine, uridine 5′-monophosphate is produced.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil undergoes amide-imidic acid tautomeric shifts because any nuclear instability the molecule may have from the lack of formal aromaticity is compensated by the cyclic-amidic stability.
[src:uracil/uracil] The amide tautomer is referred to as the lactam structure, while the imidic acid tautomer is referred to as the lactim structure.
[src:uracil/uracil] These tautomeric forms are predominant at pH 7.
[src:uracil/uracil] The lactam structure is the most common form of uracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil also recycles itself to form nucleotides by undergoing a series of phosphoribosyltransferase reactions.
[src:uracil/uracil] Degradation of uracil produces the substrates β-alanine, carbon dioxide, and ammonia.
[src:uracil/uracil] Oxidative degradation of uracil produces urea and maleic acid in the presence of H2O2 and Fe2+ or in the presence of diatomic oxygen and Fe2+.
[src:uracil/uracil] The first site of ionization of uracil is not known.
[src:uracil/uracil] The negative charge is placed on the oxygen anion and produces a p*K*a of less than or equal to 12.
[src:uracil/uracil] In the gas phase, uracil has four sites that are more acidic than water.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil is rarely found in DNA, and this may have been an evolutionary change to increase genetic stability.
[src:uracil/uracil] This is because cytosine can deaminate spontaneously to produce uracil through hydrolytic deamination.
[src:uracil/uracil] Therefore, if there were an organism that used uracil in its DNA, the deamination of cytosine (which undergoes base pairing with guanine) would lead to formation of uracil (which would base pair with adenine) during DNA synthesis.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil-DNA glycosylase excises uracil bases from double-stranded DNA.
[src:uracil/uracil] This enzyme would therefore recognize and cut out both types of uracil – the one incorporated naturally, and the one formed due to cytosine deamination, which would trigger unnecessary and inappropriate repair processes.
[src:uracil/uracil] This problem is believed to have been solved in terms of evolution, that is by "tagging" (methylating) uracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] Methylated uracil is identical to thymine.
[src:uracil/uracil] Hence the hypothesis that, over time, thymine became standard in DNA instead of uracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] So cells continue to use uracil in RNA, and not in DNA, because RNA is shorter-lived than DNA, and any potential uracil-related errors do not lead to lasting damage.
[src:uracil/uracil] Apparently, either there was no evolutionary pressure to replace uracil in RNA with the more complex thymine, or uracil has some chemical property that is useful in RNA, which thymine lacks.
[src:uracil/uracil] Organisms synthesize uracil, in the form of uridine monophosphate (UMP), by decarboxylating orotidine 5'-monophosphate (orotidylic acid).
[src:uracil/uracil] In humans this decarboxylation is achieved by the enzyme UMP synthase.
[src:uracil/uracil] In contrast to the purine nucleotides, the pyrimidine ring (orotidylic acid) that leads uracil is synthesized first and then linked to ribose phosphate, forming UMP.
[src:uracil/uracil] There are many laboratory synthesis of uracil available.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil can also be synthesized by a double decomposition of thiouracil in aqueous chloroacetic acid.
[src:uracil/uracil] Photodehydrogenation of 5,6-diuracil, which is synthesized by beta-alanine reacting with urea, produces uracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] In 2009, NASA scientists reported having produced uracil from pyrimidine and water ice by exposing it to ultraviolet light under space-like conditions.
[src:uracil/uracil] This suggests a possible natural original source for uracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] Pyrimidine, like polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), a carbon-rich chemical found in the Universe, may have been formed in red giants or in interstellar dust and gas clouds.
[src:uracil/uracil] Based on 12C/13C isotopic ratios of organic compounds found in the Murchison meteorite, it is believed that uracil, xanthine, and related molecules can also be formed extraterrestrially.
[src:uracil/uracil] Data from the Cassini mission, orbiting in the Saturn system, suggests that uracil is present on the surface of the moon Titan.
[src:uracil/uracil] In 2023, uracil was observed in a sample from 162173 Ryugu, a near-Earth asteroid, with no exposure to Earth's biosphere, giving further evidence for synthesis in space.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil readily undergoes regular reactions including oxidation, nitration, and alkylation.
[src:uracil/uracil] While in the presence of phenol (PhOH) and sodium hypochlorite (NaOCl), uracil can be visualized in ultraviolet light.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil also has the capability to react with elemental halogens because of the presence of more than one strongly electron donating group.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil readily undergoes addition to ribose sugars and phosphates to partake in synthesis and further reactions in the body.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil becomes uridine, uridine monophosphate (UMP), uridine diphosphate (UDP), uridine triphosphate (UTP), and uridine diphosphate glucose (UDP-glucose).
[src:uracil/uracil] Each one of these molecules is synthesized in the body and has specific functions.
[src:uracil/uracil] When uracil reacts with anhydrous hydrazine, a first-order kinetic reaction occurs and the uracil ring opens up.
[src:uracil/uracil] If the pH of the reaction increases to > 10.5, the uracil anion forms, making the reaction go much more slowly.
[src:uracil/uracil] The same slowing of the reaction occurs if the pH decreases, because of the protonation of the hydrazine.
[src:uracil/uracil] The reactivity of uracil remains unchanged, even if the temperature changes.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil's use in the body is to help carry out the synthesis of many enzymes necessary for cell function through bonding with riboses and phosphates.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil serves as allosteric regulator and coenzyme for reactions in animals and in plants.
[src:uracil/uracil] UMP controls the activity of carbamoyl phosphate synthetase and aspartate transcarbamoylase in plants, while UDP and UTP regulate CPSase II activity in animals.
[src:uracil/uracil] UDP-glucose regulates the conversion of glucose to galactose in the liver and other tissues in the process of carbohydrate metabolism.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil is also involved in the biosynthesis of polysaccharides and the transportation of sugars containing aldehydes.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil is important for the detoxification of many carcinogens, for instance those found in tobacco smoke.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil is also required to detoxify many drugs such as cannabinoids (THC) and morphine (opioids).
[src:uracil/uracil] It can also slightly increase the risk for cancer in unusual cases in which the body is extremely deficient in folate.
[src:uracil/uracil] The deficiency in folate leads to increased ratio of deoxyuridine monophosphates (dUMP)/deoxythymidine monophosphates (dTMP) and uracil misincorporation into DNA and eventually low production of DNA.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil can be used for drug delivery and as a pharmaceutical.
[src:uracil/uracil] When elemental fluorine reacts with uracil, they produce 5-fluorouracil.
[src:uracil/uracil] 5-Fluorouracil is an anticancer drug (antimetabolite) used to masquerade as uracil during the nucleic acid replication process.
[src:uracil/uracil] Because 5-fluorouracil is similar in shape to, but does not undergo the same chemistry as, uracil, the drug inhibits RNA transcription enzymes, thereby blocking RNA synthesis and stopping the growth of cancerous cells.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil can also be used in the synthesis of caffeine.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil has also shown potential as a HIV viral capsid inhibitor.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil derivatives have antiviral, anti-tubercular and anti-leishmanial activity.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil can be used to determine microbial contamination of tomatoes.
[src:uracil/uracil] The presence of uracil indicates lactic acid bacteria contamination of the fruit.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil derivatives containing a diazine ring are used in pesticides.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil derivatives are more often used as antiphotosynthetic herbicides, destroying weeds in cotton, sugar beet, turnips, soya, peas, sunflower crops, vineyards, berry plantations, and orchards.
[src:uracil/uracil] Uracil derivatives can enhance the activity of antimicrobial polysaccharides such as chitosan.
[src:uracil/uracil] In yeast, uracil concentrations are inversely proportional to uracil permease.
[src:uracil/uracil] Mixtures containing uracil are also commonly used to test reversed-phase HPLC columns.
[src:uracil/uracil] As uracil is essentially unretained by the non-polar stationary phase, this can be used to determine the dwell time (and subsequently dwell volume, given a known flow rate) of the system.
